 `LIKE` searches will work, it&#39;s just that, they&#39;re generally much slower because they have to access the row and not the index. Using wildcards on both sides of the comparator guarantees it won&#39;t use the index with a `LIKE`^. 

However, if you make the field `FULLTEXT` searchable, you get better search tools, including substring matching. MySQL after 5.6 allows you to use `FULLTEXT` on InnoDB, too.

